 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While most PIPE participants are institutional i=
nvestors, they sometimes include strategic investors.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">And that=E2=80=99s where Palantir (ticker: PLTR) comes in.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To date, Palantir has participated in at least e=
ight SPAC-related PIPE transactions, investing well over $100 million, usin=
g the deals as a way to win business from emerging companies that can benef=
it from Palantir=E2=80=99s big data analytics software. In effect, Palantir=
 is providing capital up front in return for a multiyear commitments to use=
 the company=E2=80=99s software.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Obviously Palantir could just go buy stock in public companies, on the s=
tock exchange,=C2=A0if it wanted to, but it doesn=E2=80=99t; that has none =
of the relationship-building advantages of this. Or it could invest in vent=
ure rounds, if it wanted to, but those are sometimes small and exclusive. A=
 SPAC PIPE is like a venture round but for an about-to-be-public company.</=
p>
